Note:
Runtime event loop — the epoll-based reactor core of the Runa async runtime.

This module is the readiness engine that the rest of the async runtime is
built on. It owns a single Linux epoll instance and turns kernel readiness
notifications into Runa callback dispatches. A higher layer (futures, tasks,
timers, network streams) registers a file descriptor together with an event
mask and a callback; when the kernel reports that descriptor ready, this loop
invokes the callback with the caller-supplied argument. The loop does NOT
own the file descriptors it watches and does NOT interpret what readiness
means for any particular subsystem — it is purely the demultiplexer.

Mechanism: the readiness primitive is the OS epoll facility, reached through
the completed platform syscall facade (epoll_create1 / epoll_ctl /
epoll_wait / close). This module does not re-implement polling; it wraps the
raw facade in a RuntimeEventLoop object plus a per-descriptor Registration
object, adds growable bookkeeping so registrations can be enumerated for
clean teardown, and exposes a stable status-code contract.

RuntimeEventLoop layout (56 bytes):
    offset 0:   epfd        — the epoll instance file descriptor
    offset 8:   result_buf  — preallocated epoll_event array (capacity * 12)
    offset 16:  capacity    — number of epoll_event slots in result_buf
    offset 24:  reg_list    — growable array of Registration pointers (8 each)
    offset 32:  reg_cap     — number of pointer slots in reg_list
    offset 40:  reg_count   — number of live registrations (also active count)
    offset 48:  running     — 0 stopped, 1 running (drives event_loop_run)

Registration layout (32 bytes):
    offset 0:   fd          — the watched file descriptor
    offset 8:   events_mask — the epoll event mask registered for fd
    offset 16:  callback_fn — the $name function pointer dispatched on ready
    offset 24:  user_arg    — opaque argument passed to callback_fn

epoll_event ABI (PACKED, 12 bytes — load-bearing):
    offset 0:   events  — u32 event mask, written with memory_set_int32
    offset 4:   data    — u64 user data, written with memory_set_int64;
                          here it holds the Registration pointer
    The kernel reads and writes a packed 12-byte record (NOT the 16-byte
    naturally-aligned shape). EPOLL_EVENT_SIZE is therefore 12, and the
    result buffer is strided by 12 so epoll_wait fills consecutive records
    without gaps. memory_set_int32 exists in the layout primitives, so the
    events field is written directly as a clean 4-byte store at offset 0 and
    the data pointer as a clean 8-byte store at offset 4 — no overlapping
    int64-overwrite trick is required.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/platform/linux_x86_64/syscall.runa" as Sys
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/call_indirect.runa" as Call

Note: RuntimeEventLoop object layout
Constant EVLOOP_SIZE as Integer is 56
Constant EVLOOP_OFF_EPFD as Integer is 0
Constant EVLOOP_OFF_BUFFER as Integer is 8
Constant EVLOOP_OFF_CAPACITY as Integer is 16
Constant EVLOOP_OFF_REG_LIST as Integer is 24
Constant EVLOOP_OFF_REG_CAP as Integer is 32
Constant EVLOOP_OFF_REG_COUNT as Integer is 40
Constant EVLOOP_OFF_RUNNING as Integer is 48

Note: Registration object layout
Constant REG_SIZE as Integer is 32
Constant REG_OFF_FD as Integer is 0
Constant REG_OFF_EVENTS as Integer is 8
Constant REG_OFF_CALLBACK as Integer is 16
Constant REG_OFF_USERARG as Integer is 24

Note: Packed epoll_event ABI — 12 bytes, NOT 16
Constant EPOLL_EVENT_SIZE as Integer is 12
Constant EPOLL_EV_OFF_EVENTS as Integer is 0
Constant EPOLL_EV_OFF_DATA as Integer is 4

Note: Size of one pointer slot in the registration list
Constant PTR_SIZE as Integer is 8

Note: Default sizing — result buffer slots and initial registration capacity
Constant EVLOOP_DEFAULT_CAPACITY as Integer is 64
Constant EVLOOP_DEFAULT_REG_CAPACITY as Integer is 8

Note: epoll_ctl operations
Constant EPOLL_CTL_ADD as Integer is 1
Constant EPOLL_CTL_DEL as Integer is 2
Constant EPOLL_CTL_MOD as Integer is 3

Note: epoll event-mask flags
Constant EPOLLIN as Integer is 1
Constant EPOLLOUT as Integer is 4
Constant EPOLLERR as Integer is 8
Constant EPOLLHUP as Integer is 16
Constant EPOLLET as Integer is 2147483648

Note: epoll_create1 flag — set close-on-exec on the epoll fd
Constant EPOLL_CLOEXEC as Integer is 524288

Note: Blocking timeout sentinel for epoll_wait (wait indefinitely)
Constant EVLOOP_TIMEOUT_BLOCK as Integer is 0 minus 1

Note: NULL event pointer accepted by EPOLL_CTL_DEL on modern kernels
Constant EVLOOP_NULL_EVENT as Integer is 0

Note: -EINTR — epoll_wait interrupted by a signal; a benign, retryable result
Constant EVLOOP_NEG_EINTR as Integer is 0 minus 4

Note: Status codes returned by the runtime event loop API
Constant EVLOOP_OK as Integer is 0
Constant EVLOOP_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1
Constant EVLOOP_ERR_CREATE as Integer is 0 minus 2
Constant EVLOOP_ERR_CTL as Integer is 0 minus 3
Constant EVLOOP_ERR_WAIT as Integer is 0 minus 4
Constant EVLOOP_ERR_ALLOC as Integer is 0 minus 5

Process called "event_loop_new" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Construct a reactor. The readiness mechanism is a single OS epoll instance
    created with EPOLL_CLOEXEC so it is not leaked across an exec. The object
    additionally carries a preallocated epoll_wait result buffer (so the hot
    polling path never allocates) and a growable registration list (so every
    live registration can be enumerated and torn down deterministically).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Create the epoll fd first; a negative return means the kernel refused the
    instance, so report failure (0) before any allocation. Then allocate, in
    order, the loop object, the result buffer (capacity * 12 packed records),
    and the registration pointer list. Each allocation failure unwinds every
    resource already acquired — earlier allocations are freed and the epoll fd
    is closed — so a failed constructor leaks nothing. Initialize reg_count and
    running to 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One epoll_create1 syscall plus three allocations, all on the cold
    construction path. The 64-slot result buffer (768 bytes) is sized so the
    common ready-set fits without a second epoll_wait round-trip.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Failure returns 0 (NULL); callers MUST check before use. EPOLL_CLOEXEC
    prevents the epoll descriptor from surviving into child processes.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let epfd be proc linux_x86_64_syscall_epoll_create1 from Sys with EPOLL_CLOEXEC
    If epfd is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let loop be proc allocate from Memory with EVLOOP_SIZE
    If loop is equal to 0:
        proc linux_x86_64_syscall_close from Sys with epfd
        Return 0
    End If

    Let capacity be EVLOOP_DEFAULT_CAPACITY
    Let buffer_bytes be capacity multiplied by EPOLL_EVENT_SIZE
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Memory with buffer_bytes
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with loop
        proc linux_x86_64_syscall_close from Sys with epfd
        Return 0
    End If

    Let reg_cap be EVLOOP_DEFAULT_REG_CAPACITY
    Let reg_bytes be reg_cap multiplied by PTR_SIZE
    Let reg_list be proc allocate from Memory with reg_bytes
    If reg_list is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with buffer
        proc deallocate from Memory with loop
        proc linux_x86_64_syscall_close from Sys with epfd
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_EPFD, epfd
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_BUFFER, buffer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_CAPACITY, capacity
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_LIST, reg_list
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_CAP, reg_cap
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_COUNT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_RUNNING, 0
    Return loop
End Process

Process called "event_loop_add" takes loop as Integer, fd as Integer, events as Integer, callback as Integer, user_arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Register a descriptor for readiness notification. The Registration object
    is the durable record of "who to call when fd is ready"; its pointer is
    handed to the kernel as the epoll_event data word so that when the fd later
    becomes ready, epoll_wait returns that exact pointer and dispatch is an
    O(1) field read rather than a search keyed on the descriptor.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate and populate a 32-byte Registration (fd, mask, callback, arg).
    Build a packed 12-byte epoll_event on a scratch allocation: the u32 mask
    is written at offset 0 with memory_set_int32 and the Registration pointer
    is written at offset 4 with memory_set_int64 (the kernel reads the 8-byte
    data word starting at offset 4 of the packed record). Submit it with
    EPOLL_CTL_ADD, then free the scratch event — the kernel has copied it. On
    a control failure the Registration is freed and EVLOOP_ERR_CTL returned.
    On success the Registration pointer is appended to the registration list,
    doubling the list first if it is full; copy via memory_copy and free the
    old backing store. If the list grow itself fails, the ADD is rolled back
    with EPOLL_CTL_DEL so loop bookkeeping never diverges from kernel state.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One allocation for the Registration plus one scratch allocation for the
    event record, one epoll_ctl syscall, and an amortized-O(1) list append.
    The doubling growth keeps total copying linear across the loop's lifetime.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null loop returns EVLOOP_ERR_NULL without touching memory. The caller
    retains ownership of fd; this loop only references it. The callback pointer
    is invoked verbatim later via call_indirect_1, matching that primitive's
    contract — the caller is responsible for supplying a valid $name pointer.
    @End Security_Scope

    If loop is equal to 0:
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let reg be proc allocate from Memory with REG_SIZE
    If reg is equal to 0:
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_ALLOC
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with reg, REG_OFF_FD, fd
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with reg, REG_OFF_EVENTS, events
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with reg, REG_OFF_CALLBACK, callback
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with reg, REG_OFF_USERARG, user_arg

    Let ev be proc allocate from Memory with EPOLL_EVENT_SIZE
    If ev is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with reg
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_ALLOC
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with ev, EPOLL_EV_OFF_EVENTS, events
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ev, EPOLL_EV_OFF_DATA, reg

    Let epfd be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_EPFD
    Let rc be proc linux_x86_64_syscall_epoll_ctl from Sys with epfd, EPOLL_CTL_ADD, fd, ev
    proc deallocate from Memory with ev
    If rc is less than 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with reg
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_CTL
    End If

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_COUNT
    Let cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_CAP
    If count is equal to cap:
        Let new_cap be cap multiplied by 2
        If new_cap is equal to 0:
            Set new_cap to EVLOOP_DEFAULT_REG_CAPACITY
        End If
        Let new_bytes be new_cap multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let new_list be proc allocate from Memory with new_bytes
        If new_list is equal to 0:
            proc linux_x86_64_syscall_epoll_ctl from Sys with epfd, EPOLL_CTL_DEL, fd, EVLOOP_NULL_EVENT
            proc deallocate from Memory with reg
            Return EVLOOP_ERR_ALLOC
        End If
        Let old_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_LIST
        Let copy_bytes be count multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        proc memory_copy from Memory with new_list, old_list, copy_bytes
        proc deallocate from Memory with old_list
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_LIST, new_list
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_CAP, new_cap
    End If

    Let list be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_LIST
    Let slot_offset be count multiplied by PTR_SIZE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with list, slot_offset, reg
    Let new_count be count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_COUNT, new_count
    Return EVLOOP_OK
End Process

Process called "event_loop_modify" takes loop as Integer, fd as Integer, events as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Change the event mask for an already-registered descriptor without tearing
    down and recreating its Registration, so the callback identity and any
    pending kernel state for fd are preserved across the change.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Linearly locate the Registration whose fd matches (the registration set is
    small and walked rarely). Update its stored mask, build a fresh packed
    12-byte epoll_event carrying the new mask at offset 0 and the unchanged
    Registration pointer at offset 4, and submit it with EPOLL_CTL_MOD. The
    scratch event is freed after the syscall. A missing fd is reported as
    EVLOOP_ERR_NULL; a kernel control failure as EVLOOP_ERR_CTL.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One linear scan over the live registrations, one scratch allocation, and
    one epoll_ctl syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null loop returns EVLOOP_ERR_NULL. Modifying an unregistered fd is a
    caller error surfaced as EVLOOP_ERR_NULL rather than a silent no-op.
    @End Security_Scope

    If loop is equal to 0:
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_COUNT
    Let list be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_LIST
    Let found be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let slot_offset be i multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let candidate be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with list, slot_offset
        Let candidate_fd be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with candidate, REG_OFF_FD
        If candidate_fd is equal to fd:
            Set found to candidate
            Set i to count
        Otherwise:
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While

    If found is equal to 0:
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_NULL
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with found, REG_OFF_EVENTS, events

    Let ev be proc allocate from Memory with EPOLL_EVENT_SIZE
    If ev is equal to 0:
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_ALLOC
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with ev, EPOLL_EV_OFF_EVENTS, events
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ev, EPOLL_EV_OFF_DATA, found

    Let epfd be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_EPFD
    Let rc be proc linux_x86_64_syscall_epoll_ctl from Sys with epfd, EPOLL_CTL_MOD, fd, ev
    proc deallocate from Memory with ev
    If rc is less than 0:
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_CTL
    End If
    Return EVLOOP_OK
End Process

Process called "event_loop_remove" takes loop as Integer, fd as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Stop watching a descriptor and reclaim its Registration. Removal must keep
    the registration list dense so the active count stays accurate and future
    scans stay cheap.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Locate the index of the Registration matching fd. Detach the fd from epoll
    with EPOLL_CTL_DEL (a NULL event pointer is accepted for DEL). Compact the
    list by moving the last pointer into the vacated slot (a no-op when the
    removed entry was already last), decrement reg_count, and free the
    Registration. The DEL result is captured: even if the kernel reports the fd
    was already gone (for example the caller closed it first), the loop's own
    bookkeeping is still reclaimed, and the DEL status is surfaced so callers
    learn of an unexpected control failure.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One linear scan, one epoll_ctl syscall, an O(1) swap-compaction, and one
    deallocate. No buffer shrink — capacity is retained for reuse.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null loop returns EVLOOP_ERR_NULL. Removing an unregistered fd returns
    EVLOOP_ERR_NULL without altering any state.
    @End Security_Scope

    If loop is equal to 0:
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_COUNT
    Let list be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_LIST
    Let idx be 0 minus 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let slot_offset be i multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let candidate be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with list, slot_offset
        Let candidate_fd be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with candidate, REG_OFF_FD
        If candidate_fd is equal to fd:
            Set idx to i
            Set i to count
        Otherwise:
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While

    If idx is less than 0:
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let idx_offset be idx multiplied by PTR_SIZE
    Let reg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with list, idx_offset

    Let epfd be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_EPFD
    Let rc be proc linux_x86_64_syscall_epoll_ctl from Sys with epfd, EPOLL_CTL_DEL, fd, EVLOOP_NULL_EVENT

    Let last_idx be count minus 1
    If idx is not equal to last_idx:
        Let last_offset be last_idx multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let last_reg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with list, last_offset
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with list, idx_offset, last_reg
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_COUNT, last_idx
    proc deallocate from Memory with reg

    If rc is less than 0:
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_CTL
    End If
    Return EVLOOP_OK
End Process

Process called "event_loop_run_once" takes loop as Integer, timeout_ms as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Perform a single reactor turn: ask the kernel which descriptors are ready
    within the timeout, then dispatch each ready descriptor's callback. This is
    the hot path; one epoll_wait drives every dispatch in the turn.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Call epoll_wait into the preallocated result buffer for up to capacity
    records. A negative return is an error: -EINTR (a signal interrupted the
    wait) is benign and reported as 0 events dispatched so callers simply retry
    the turn; any other negative is reported as EVLOOP_ERR_WAIT. For each of the
    N returned packed 12-byte records, read the Registration pointer from the
    data word at offset 4, load its callback and user_arg, and invoke the
    callback via call_indirect_1. A null Registration or null callback record
    is skipped defensively. Returns N, the number of callbacks dispatched.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Exactly one epoll_wait syscall per turn. Dispatch is a tight loop of two
    field loads and one indirect call per ready descriptor, striding the result
    buffer by the packed 12-byte record size with no per-event allocation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null loop returns EVLOOP_ERR_NULL. The Registration pointer read back from
    the kernel data word is exactly the one this loop stored at registration
    time, so dispatch cannot be redirected by descriptor-number reuse.
    @End Security_Scope

    If loop is equal to 0:
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let epfd be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_EPFD
    Let buffer be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_BUFFER
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_CAPACITY

    Let n be proc linux_x86_64_syscall_epoll_wait from Sys with epfd, buffer, capacity, timeout_ms
    If n is less than 0:
        If n is equal to EVLOOP_NEG_EINTR:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_WAIT
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than n:
        Let record_offset be i multiplied by EPOLL_EVENT_SIZE
        Let record_ptr be buffer plus record_offset
        Let reg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with record_ptr, EPOLL_EV_OFF_DATA
        If reg is not equal to 0:
            Let callback be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with reg, REG_OFF_CALLBACK
            Let user_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with reg, REG_OFF_USERARG
            If callback is not equal to 0:
                proc call_indirect_1 from Call with callback, user_arg
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return n
End Process

Process called "event_loop_run" takes loop as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Drive the reactor until it is asked to stop or has nothing left to watch.
    Running with no registrations leaves epoll_wait blocked indefinitely, so
    the loop also exits when the active registration count reaches zero.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Set running to 1, then repeatedly run a blocking turn (timeout -1). The
    bootstrap compiler has no compound boolean operators in a condition, so the
    "still running AND has registrations" decision is expressed with a
    should_continue flag set by nested Ifs: clear it when running drops to 0,
    when the active count reaches 0, or when a turn reports a hard
    EVLOOP_ERR_WAIT (so a persistent kernel error cannot spin the loop). An
    interrupted wait (-EINTR) is reported by run_once as 0 and simply retried.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Blocks in the kernel between events (timeout -1), so an idle loop consumes
    no CPU. Each wake performs exactly one turn's dispatch before re-arming.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null loop returns EVLOOP_ERR_NULL. event_loop_stop may be called from a
    dispatched callback to request an orderly shutdown after the current turn.
    @End Security_Scope

    If loop is equal to 0:
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_NULL
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_RUNNING, 1

    Let should_continue be 1
    While should_continue is equal to 1:
        Let running be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_RUNNING
        If running is equal to 0:
            Set should_continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let active be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_COUNT
            If active is equal to 0:
                Set should_continue to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let rc be event_loop_run_once(loop, EVLOOP_TIMEOUT_BLOCK)
                If rc is less than 0:
                    Set should_continue to 0
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While
    Return EVLOOP_OK
End Process

Process called "event_loop_stop" takes loop as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Request an orderly shutdown of event_loop_run. Stopping only clears the
    running flag; the loop exits after the in-flight turn completes, so a
    callback that calls stop still returns cleanly.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Set the running flag to 0. The next iteration of event_loop_run's guard
    observes it and exits.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field store.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null loop returns EVLOOP_ERR_NULL. Safe to call from any thread or from
    within a dispatched callback; the flag is read once per turn.
    @End Security_Scope

    If loop is equal to 0:
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_RUNNING, 0
    Return EVLOOP_OK
End Process

Process called "event_loop_active_count" takes loop as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report how many descriptors are currently registered, which is the figure
    that decides whether event_loop_run has any work left.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return the reg_count field, which is kept exactly equal to the number of
    live Registrations by add (increment) and remove (decrement with
    compaction).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null loop returns 0. Pure read.
    @End Security_Scope

    If loop is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_COUNT
End Process

Process called "event_loop_destroy" takes loop as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Fully tear down a reactor with no leaks: every live Registration is
    detached from the kernel and freed, then the epoll fd is closed and all
    backing allocations are released. This is why the loop tracks its
    registrations — without the list, the per-fd Registration objects could not
    be reclaimed.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Walk the registration list. For each live Registration, detach its fd with
    EPOLL_CTL_DEL (NULL event) and free the Registration. Free the registration
    list backing store, free the epoll_wait result buffer, close the epoll fd,
    and finally free the loop object itself.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One epoll_ctl plus one deallocate per registration, then one close and
    three deallocates. Cold path: done once per loop.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null loop returns EVLOOP_ERR_NULL. After destroy the loop pointer is
    dangling and must not be reused. Descriptors are detached, not closed —
    their ownership stays with the original registrant.
    @End Security_Scope

    If loop is equal to 0:
        Return EVLOOP_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let epfd be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_EPFD
    Let list be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_LIST
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_REG_COUNT

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let slot_offset be i multiplied by PTR_SIZE
        Let reg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with list, slot_offset
        If reg is not equal to 0:
            Let reg_fd be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with reg, REG_OFF_FD
            proc linux_x86_64_syscall_epoll_ctl from Sys with epfd, EPOLL_CTL_DEL, reg_fd, EVLOOP_NULL_EVENT
            proc deallocate from Memory with reg
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc deallocate from Memory with list
    Let buffer be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with loop, EVLOOP_OFF_BUFFER
    proc deallocate from Memory with buffer
    proc linux_x86_64_syscall_close from Sys with epfd
    proc deallocate from Memory with loop
    Return EVLOOP_OK
End Process
